Minecraft hardcore tips that are not ‚Äúgit gud‚Äù
 Aka these won‚Äôt save you from everything but it‚Äôll prevent a lot of deaths. You do not have to be an excellent pve‚Äôer to survive in hardcore it just helps a lot
 The first priority is food, followed by a bed. The more mobs you can prevent from spawning, the better. Your base is now the first place you manage to make a house in before night falls - plains are good for this but don‚Äôt go looking for one until day.
 TAKE YOUR BED/A BED WITH YOU WHEN YOU LEAVE BASE FOR EXTENDED PERIODS OF TIME. Skipping night usually means nothing can spawn as long as you sleep immediately.
 Next is torches. You can use logs to make charcoal, and charcoal can be used to make them. Torch spam your entire area, so that you can‚Äôt see any unlit areas from your base. This will prevent spawns nearby, which gives you an almost forcefeild against mobs - if you‚Äôre a couple chunks (16x16 blocks) from the nearest mob it won‚Äôt pathfind to you. And the fewer mobs spawn, the less chance of a hoard. 
 Don‚Äôt set up near rivers or oceans unless you‚Äôre good with a shield. Tridents can kill you in enchanted netherite in about 6 hits.
 If you are not good with a shield, that‚Äôs fine. Prioritize armour. You can find diamonds when stripmining still - they‚Äôre at bedrock level. Keep your tunnels lit. If you want netherite it‚Äôs frankly safest if you have fire resistance, but you can get by with food and a set of blast and fire prot armour. Don‚Äôt make it from diamonds unless you‚Äôre farming villager trades.
 A water bucket is extremely helpful, and so is just. Placing water under yourself. Effective shield against mobs touching you. Likewise, endermen will not teleport into water - if you need time to regen health, place water or jump into a pond or lake. 
 Redstone and making farms for items is EXTREMELY helpful. Tutorials are pretty easy to find for just about everything you could want to farm, too. Some are more labor intensive than others. 
 Feel free to reblog with the things you do too :] Minecraft doesn‚Äôt have to be a git gud game. 
 Look up, look out. Drop-creepers in ravines and caves are your deadliest foe in the overworld.
 Going to the nether? Wear something gold. And remember that piglins will not run away from soul fire if they're aggro on you.
 Found a village? Stay there! Villagers make iron golems happen, and so long as you don't join in the combat and hit a friendly target, you've got protection from everything except creepers.
 Likewise, if you find a village get yourself all the sticks and train up villagers to sell you diamond gear.
 Don't set special rules (i.e. no villager trading) until you feel comfy. Extra challenges might be great if you were making a video/stream series, but even then don't jump in the deep end, make it a multi-series where you add new rules every time you succeed or something.
 Don't measure yourself against people who play the game as their job. Do your own thing.
 Have fun.

 . They‚Äôre not avoidable and even armour can‚Äôt always save you unless it‚Äôs blast prot. 
 While we‚Äôre on the topic of armour enchants, I cannot sing the praise enough of a full set of thorns three if you‚Äôre not good at combat. Be advised that it will drain your armour‚Äôs durability, so if you‚Äôre using it make sure you have a way to fix it - either extra diamonds or mending and a way to get exp. It buys you extra time to aim, and if you have the right enchants on the other pieces, you can straight up just let skeletons die to your armour if you don‚Äôt wanna go to them.
 If creepers cannot get within a few blocks from you, or there‚Äôs a solid barrier of impassable blocks between you and it, the creeper will not explode. So if one is lurking outside your door, don‚Äôt sweat. The ai will direct it off in a random direction if you stay safe from it for long enough.
